  "why": "The paper does more than report failures: it analyzes discovered misinterpretations to identify the underlying vulnerability (the NLU Intent Classifier and its template-based design) and characterizes failure modes that point to concrete root causes and mitigations. Concretely, the authors (1) empirically isolate the source of failures by removing ASR effects (synthesizing transcripts and replaying them) and show that most failures persist, attributing them to the Intent Classifier; (2) categorize LAPSUS (failure) types at pronunciation, vocabulary, and grammar levels and build statistical (BN) models that capture which linguistic transitions produce failures; (3) measure population-level patterns (store-wide counts and sampled verification rates) and show concentration of failures in templates/installation-invocation names; and (4) draw actionable implications (e.g., simple/unique names reduce risk). These analyses link observed failures to concrete model/design vulnerabilities (template-based intent matching, fuzzy-matching behavior, slot/name design), satisfying the metric requirement of explaining why failures occur and pointing to remediation directions.",
